    MACHINE TOOLS AND METROLOGY
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Metal cutting: Introduction, elements of cutting process – Geometry of single point tools. Chip formation and types of chips, Merchant circle diagram, Role of cutting fluids. Engine lathe – Principle of working, specifications. Taper turning, – Lathe attachments. Capstan and Turret lathe

    UNIT-2

    Drilling Machines – Principles of working, types (Radial, gang, multi spindle), operations performed; twist drill. Boring Machine - Types of Boring machines and applications. Introduction to Slotting Machine.

    UNIT-3

    Milling machines – Principles of working – Types of milling machines (Horizontal and vertical machine) – Types of milling cutters, methods of indexing. Grinding – classification of grinding machines. Types of abrasives, bonds. Selection of a grinding wheel. Introduction to Lapping, honing and broaching machines.

    UNIT-4

    Limits, fits and tolerances- Unilateral and bilateral tolerance system, hole and shaft basis system. Limit Gauges: Taylor‘s principle, Design of GO and NO GO gauges Measurement of angles, Bevel protractor, and Sine bar. Measurement of flat surfaces, straight edges, surface plates, optical flat and auto collimator.

    UNIT-5

    Measurements: Roughness, Waviness, RMS, Rz Values. Method of measurement of surface finish, Talysurf, Screw thread measurement, Gear measurement; Machine Tool Alignment Tests on lathe, milling and drilling machines. Coordinate Measuring Machines: Types and Applications of CMM


    DESIGN OF TRANSMISSION ELEMENTS
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Design of Shafts: Design of solid and hollow shafts for strength and rigidity - Design of shafts for complex loads - Shaft sizes - BIS code -Design of shaft for a gear and belt drives. Shaft Couplings: Rigid couplings – Muff, Split muff and Flange couplings. Flexible couplings – Pin – Bush Couplings.

    UNIT-2

    UNIT – II Spur and Helical Gear Design: Spur Gears: Definitions, stresses in gear tooth: Lewis equation and form factor, Design for strength, Dynamic load and wear load. Helical Gears: Definitions, formative number of teeth, Design based on strength, dynamic and wear loads.

    UNIT-3

    Bevel Gear Design: Definitions, formative number of teeth, Design based on strength, dynamic and wear loads. Worm gear design Worm Gears: Definitions, Design based on strength, dynamic, wear loads and efficiency of worm gear drives

    UNIT-4

    Sliding Contact Bearings: Types of journal bearings- basic modes of Lubrication- Bearing construction – bearing design – bearing materials – selection of lubricants Rolling Contact Bearings: Types of rolling contact bearings- selection of bearing type- selection of bearing life – design for cyclic loads and speeds- Static and dynamic loading of ball & roller bearings.

    UNIT-5

    Belt Drives: Flat Belt Drive: Belt Construction, Flat Belt Drive: Length of the Belt: Open and Cross drive types, Ratio of Tensions on tight side to slack side, Condition for maximum power transmission, Creep phenomenon, Methods for tensioning, Selection of Belts from catalogues, Design of Pulley for flat belt drive. V-Belt Drive: Nomenclature, Selection of V-Belts from catalogues. Rope And Chain Drives: Rope drives-materials- Transmission of power by rope drive-Chain drives- Classification of chains-Transmission efficiency-Pulleys for rope drives. Design of IC Engine Parts(self-study/assignment): Design of piston, Cylinder, connecting rod and crank shaft-.


    Heat Transfer
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction: Modes of heat transfer, Basic laws of heat transfer, General heat conduction equation in Cartesian, Cylindrical and Spherical coordinates- Simplification and forms of the field equation – steady, unsteady and periodic heat transfer – Initial and boundary conditions

    UNIT-2

    One Dimensional Steady State Conduction Heat Transfer: Homogeneous slabs, hollow cylinders and spheres, concept of conduction and film resistances, overall heat transfer coefficient, electrical analogy, critical radius of insulation, Variable Thermal conductivity – introduction to systems with heat sources, heat transfer through fins, Introduction to finite difference methods

    UNIT-3

    One Dimensional Transient Conduction Heat Transfer: Systems with negligible internal resistance, Significance of Biot and Fourier Numbers –Heisler Chart solutions of transient conduction systems. Convective Heat Transfer: Basic equations, boundary layers, forced convection, external and internal flows, Natural convective heat transfer- Dimensionless parameters for forced and free convection heat transfer-Correlations for forced and free convection- Estimating heat transfer rates in laminar and turbulent flow situations using appropriate correlations for free and forced convection.

    UNIT-4

    Boiling: Pool boiling – Regimes- Nucleate boiling, Critical Heat flux and Film boiling Condensation: Film wise and drop wise condensation –Nusselt‘s Theory of Condensation on a vertical plate - Film condensation on vertical and horizontal cylinders using empirical correlations

    UNIT-5

    Radiation Heat Transfer: Emission characteristics and laws of black-body radiation – Irradiation– total and monochromatic quantities-laws of Planck, Wien, Kirchoff, Lambert, Stefan and Boltzmann– heat exchange between two blackbodies – concepts of shape factor – heat exchange between grey bodies – radiation shields– electrical analogy for radiation networks. Heat exchangers: Types, overall heat transfer coefficient and fouling factor, Analysis of heat exchangers using both LMTD and ε-NTU methods

    MECHANICS OF COMPOSITE MATERIALS
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Basic Concepts and Characteristics: Geometric and Physical definitions, natural and man-made composites, Aerospace and structural applications, types and classification of composites. Reinforcements: Fibers–Glass, Silica, Kevlar, carbon, boron, silicon carbide, and born carbide fibersParticulate composites, Polymer composites, Thermoplastics, Thermosets, Metal matrix and ceramic composites

    UNIT-2

    Micromechanics: Unidirectional composites, constituent materials and properties, elastic properties of a lamina, properties of typical composite materials, laminate characteristics and configurations. Characterization of composite properties Manufacturing methods: Autoclave, tape production, moulding methods, filament winding, man layup, pultrusion, RTM.

    UNIT-3

    Hooke’s Law for Different Types of Materials: Hooke’s law for two-dimensional unidirectional lamina, transformation of stress and strain, numerical examples of stress strain transformation. Graphic interpretation of stress – strain relations. off – axis, stiffness modulus, off – axis compliance. Elastic Behavior of Unidirectional Composites: Elastic constants of lamina, relationship between engineering constants and reduced stiffness and compliances, analysis of laminated composites, constitutive relations.

    UNIT-4

    Strength of Unidirectional Lamina: Micro mechanics of failure, Failure mechanisms, strength of anorthotropic lamina, strength of a lamina under tension and shear maximum stress and strain criteria, application to design. The failure envelope, first ply failure, free-edge effects- Micros mechanical predictions of elastic constants

    UNIT-5

    Analysis of Laminated Composite Plates: Introduction thin plate theory, specially orthotropic plate, cross and angle ply laminated plates, problems using thin plate theory

    Advanced Manufacturing Processes and GD&T
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction: Need for non-traditional machining methods-Classification of modern machining processes - considerations in process selection-Materials-Applications Ultrasonic machining: Elements of the process, mechanics of metal removal process parameters, economic considerations, applications and limitations, recent development.

    UNIT-2

    Abrasive Jet Machining, Water Jet Machining and Abrasive Water Jet Machining: Basic principles, equipment, process variables, mechanics of metal removal, MRR, application and limitations- Magnetic abrasive finishing, Abrasive flow finishing Electro – Chemical Processes: Fundamentals of electro chemical machining, electrochemical grinding, electro chemical honing and deburring process, metal removal rate in ECM, Tool design, Surface finish and accuracy economic aspects of ECM – Simple problems for estimation of metal removal rate

    UNIT-3

    Thermal Metal Removal Processes: Introduction to Electric Discharge Machining, Electric Discharge Grinding and electric discharge wire cutting processes – Power circuits for EDM, Mechanics of metal removal in EDM, Process parameters, tool electrode and dielectric fluids, Wire EDM, principle, applications. Electron Beam Machining: Introduction to electron beam machining, principle and applications. Introduction to laser beam machining, principle and applications.

    UNIT-4

    Introduction: GD&T, use of GD&T in drawing, Technical Standards, Dimensioning types and Tolerances types, functional dimensions, selecting a Tolerancing approach; datums and datum features. GD&T Symbols: Geometric characteristics, symbols, MMC, LMC & RFS, use of symbols, tolerance zone

    UNIT-5

    Form Tolerances: straightness, flatness, cylindricity, circularity Orientation Tolerances: parallelism, perpendicularity, angularity Datums: Specifying degrees of freedom, datum features, curves, conical, inclined Location Tolerances: position tolerance, runout tolerances, profile tolerances, concentricity & Symmetry tolerances

    REFRIGERATION AND HVAC DESIGN
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction to Refrigeration: Necessity and Applications, Definition of COP, Ton Of Refrigeration, Reversed Carnot Cycle, Eco-Friendly Refrigerants, Properties Of Refrigerants. Air Refrigeration Systems: Analysis of Bell-Coleman Cycle, Application to Aircraft Refrigeration, Simple Cooling System, Bootstrap System, Regenerative Cooling System and Reduced Ambient Cooling System

    UNIT-2

    Vapour Compression Refrigeration System: Components-Working Principle and Analysis of Simple Vapor Compression Refrigeration Cycle. T-s, P-h and h-s diagrams -Influence of various parameters on System Performance, Liquid Sub-Cooling and Vapor Super Heating.

    UNIT-3

    Vapour Absorption Refrigeration System: Components and Working o f NH3 – Water System, Li Br – Water System and Three Fluid Absorption System-Ideal COP-Comparison with Vapor Compression Refrigeration System. Steam Jet Refrigeration: Principle of working, Analysis of the system, Advantages, limitations and applications. Thermoelectric refrigeration systems: Seebeck effect, Peltier effect and Thompson effect-Vortex tube refrigeration – principle and working.

    UNIT-4

    Air Conditioning: Review of Psychometric Properties and Processes– Requirements of comfort air conditioning, Thermodynamics of human body, ASHRAE comfort chart, and Effective temperature. Cooling Load Calculations in Air Conditioning, Concept of bypass factor, Sensible heat factor, Apparatus Dew Point

    UNIT-5

    Design of air conditioning systems: Simple Problems on summer, winter and year Round Air conditioning systems-Components of air conditioning system- Humidifier, Dehumidifier, Filter. Heat Pumps: –Heat sources for heat pumps – different heat pump circuits.

    OPERATIONS RESEARCH
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction: Development – definition– characteristics and phases – types of operation research models – Applications. Allocation: Linear programming problem formulation – graphical solution – simplex method – artificial variables techniques -two–phase method, big-M method – duality principle

    UNIT-2

    Transportation Problem: Formulation – optimal solution, unbalanced transportation problem – degeneracy, assignment problem – formulation – optimal solution -variants of assignment problem- travelling salesman problem. Sequencing – Introduction – flow –shop sequencing – n jobs through two machines – n jobs through three machines – job shop sequencing – two jobs through ‘m’ machines.

    UNIT-3

    Replacement: Introduction – replacement of items that deteriorate with time – when money value is not counted and counted – replacement of items that fail completely, group replacement. Theory of games: Introduction – mini. max (max. mini) – criterion and optimal strategy – solution of games with saddle points – rectangular games without saddle points – 2x 2 games – dominance principle – m x 2 & 2 x n games -graphical method.

    UNIT-4

    Waiting Lines: Introduction – single channel – poison arrivals – exponential service times – with infinite population and finite population models– multichannel – poison arrivals– Exponential service times with infinite population single channel poison arrivals. Inventory: Introduction – single item – deterministic models – purchase inventory models with one price break and multiple price breaks – shortages are not allowed –stochastic models – demand may be discrete variable or continuous variable – instantaneous production. Instantaneous demand and continuous demand and no set up cost.

    UNIT-5

    Dynamic Programming: Introduction – Bellman’s principle of optimality –applications of dynamic programming- linear programming problem. Simulation: Definition – types of simulation models – phases of simulation–applications of simulation – inventory and queuing problems – advantages and disadvantages– brief introduction of Simulation languages.

Map Representation: Probabilistic Map-Based Localization-robot localization problem, Basic concepts of probability theory, Classification of localization problems, Markov localization, Kalman filter localization, Autonomous Map Building – SLAM, Mathematical definition, Extended Kalman Filter, Visual SLAM with a single camera, Graph-based SLAM, Particle filter SLAM, Open challenges in SLAM.

    FINITE ELEMENT METHODS
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction to FEM; Basic concepts, historical back ground, advantages, dis-advantages and application of FEM. general description. Basic equations of elasticity, Stress - Strain and strain – displacement relations- Rayleigh- Ritz method, weighted residual methods.

    UNIT-2

    One Dimensional Problems: Stiffness equations for an axial bar element in local co-ordinates using Potential Energy approach and Virtual energy principle - Finite element analysis of uniform, stepped and tapered bars subjected to mechanical and thermal loads - Assembly of Global stiffness matrix and load vector - properties of stiffness matrix.

    UNIT-3

    Trusses: Element matrices, assembling of global stiffness matrix, solution for displacements, reaction, stresses. Analysis of beams: Hermite shape functions - Element stiffness matrix- Load vector -Problems.

    UNIT-4

    Two Dimensional Problems: Basic concepts of plane stress and plane strain, stiffness matrix of CST element, finite element solution of plane stress problems. Axi-Symmetric Model: Finite element modelling of axi-symmetric solids subjected to axisymmetric loading with triangular elements.

    UNIT-5

    Heat Transfer Problems: One dimensional steady state analysis composite wall. One dimensional fin analysis and two-dimensional analysis of thin plate. Dynamic Analysis: Dynamic equations - Lumped and consistent mass matrices – Eigen Values and Eigen Vectors.

    CFD Applications in FM and HT
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction: Introduction to Computational fluid dynamics (CFD) , CFD as design and research tool, impact of CFD in Engineering, governing equations of fluid dynamics: Models flow, time rate of change (of moving fluid element), the divergence of velocity and its physical meaning, continuity, momentum and energy equations, mathematical behavior of partial differential equations

    UNIT-2

    Discretization Methods: Finite Difference Method (FDM): Application of FDM to model problems, steady and unsteady problems, implicit and explicit approaches, errors and stability analysis, direct and iterative solvers. Finite Volume Method (FVM): FVM for diffusion, convection-diffusion problem, different discretization schemes, FVM for unsteady problems, Introduction of SIMPLE,

    UNIT-3

    CFD Methodology: Different types of CFD techniques, various stages of CFD techniques (i) pre processor: governing equations, boundary conditions, grid generation, different discretization techniques (ii) processor: solution schemes, different solvers and physical setup. Post-processing: Analysis of results, verification, and validation, grid-independent studies.

    UNIT-4

    Fluid Mechanics Application: Perform Numerical analysis on flow through a pipe, compressible flow in the nozzle, steady flow past a cylinder, unsteady flow past a cylinder, flow over an airfoil.

    UNIT-5

    Heat Transfer Application: Perform heat conduction analysis for a plain and composite wall. Simple application for Natural and Forced convection Problems.

Samsung SDI: A Leader of Six Sigma in Korea. Digital Appliance Company of LG Electronics: Success Story with Six Sigma, Readiness for Six Sigma assessing the Organization, Justifying six sigma.

    OPTIMIZATION METHODS
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction to optimization: Classification of optimization problems-mathematical models in engineering optimization-Concepts in linear optimization- General simplex method- revised simplex method-duality-decomposition principle- Integer programming-branch and bound technique and the Gomory algorithm- post optimality analysis.

    UNIT-2

    Nonlinear programming without constraints: Introduction-Formulating a Non-linear Programming Problem-General Nonlinear programming problem-Local and global maxima, minima, Hessian matrix, Fibonacci method, Golden section method, random search method, steepest descent method and conjugate gradient method.

    UNIT-3

    UNIT – III Nonlinear programming with constraints: Introduction-Constrained optimization with equality constraints-Constrained optimization with inequality constraints-Lagrange multipliers-Kuhn-Tucker conditions-quadratic programming-Wolfe’s and Beale’s methodsequential linear programming approach-penalty methods-Interior and exterior penalty Geometric programming: Introduction-Geometric Mean Inequality-unconstrained geometric programming problem-Constrained geometric programming problem-complementary geometric programming problem-Complementary geometric programming algorithm.

    UNIT-4

    Advanced optimization techniques: Concepts of multi-objective optimization- genetic algorithms simulation-process of simulation-simulation models-event type simulationgeneration of random numbers-Monte Carlo simulation-Advantages and disadvantages of simulation-Case studies for simulation of investment and budgeting etc.

    UNIT-5

    Applications of optimization in design and manufacturing systems: Formulation of model- optimization of path synthesis of a four-bar mechanism, minimization of weight of a cantilever beam, general optimization model of a machining process, optimization of arc welding parameters, and general procedure in optimizing machining operations sequence

    UNIT-2

    THERMAL POWER PLANTS -II- Coal and Ash Handling Systems: Types of coals-Properties of coal, coal handling- choice of handling equipment, coal storage; Types of stokers and their working, Pulverized fuel burning system and its components, Necessity of ash disposal, Ash handling systems Steam Nozzles: Types of nozzles, velocity of steam, discharge through nozzle, critical pressure ratio and condition for maximum discharge, physical significance of critical pressure ratio, nozzle efficiency

    UNIT-3

    THERMAL POWER PLANTS –III Steam turbines: Principle of operation, types of steam turbines, compounding of steam turbines, impulse turbine – velocity diagram, calculation of work, power and efficiency, condition for maximum efficiency, Reaction turbines – velocity diagram, degree of reaction, reheat factor Condensers and Cooling Towers: Types of condensers, sources of air in condenser, Effects of air leakage, Methods of obtaining maximum vacuum in condenser, vacuum & condenser efficiency, Mass of cooling water required, Edward air pump, Necessity of cooling towers and types of cooling towers

    UNIT-4

    NUCLEAR, DIESEL AND GAS TURBINE POWER PLANTS Nuclear Power Plants: Nuclear fusion and fission, Chain reaction, Nuclear fuels, Components of nuclear reactor, Classification of reactors, Pressurized water reactor, Boiling water reactor, Gas cooled reactor, CANDU reactor, Fast breeder reactor, Nuclear waste and its disposal Diesel and Gas Turbine Power Plants: Introduction and Plant layout with auxiliaries; combined cycle power plants and comparison

    UNIT-5

    RENEWABLE ENERGY POWER AND POWER PLANT ECONOMICS Power from Renewable Energy: Hydro Electric Power Plants-Classification and Typical Layout; Schematic layout and working of Wind, Tidal, Solar Photo Voltaic, Solar Thermal, Geo Thermal, Biogas and Fuel Cell power systems Power Plant Economics: Load curves, Load duration curves, Connected load, Maximum load, Peak load, Base load and peak load power plants, Load factor, Plant capacity factor, Plant use factor, Demand factor, Diversity factor

    DESIGN AND SYNTHESIS OF MECHANISMS
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Kinematic Analysis of Mechanisms: Review of fundamentals of kinematics, mobility; Kinematic Inversions, Grashoff's law, Mechanical advantage and Transmission angle; Position analysis of four bar, Slider Crank mechanisms by vector algebra methods; Velocity, acceleration analysis of four bar, Slider Crank mechanisms by vector algebra methods.

    UNIT-2

    Kinematic Synthesis of Linkages: Introduction to synthesis, type, number and dimensional synthesis; Two position synthesis of four bar and slider crank mechanisms by extreme position and inversion methods; Three position synthesis of four bar and slider crank mechanisms by inversion method; Coupler curve synthesis; Analytical Methods of synthesis by Freudestien's Method

    UNIT-3

    Path Curvature Theory: Fixed and moving centrodes; Determination of radius of curvature of coupler points by Hartmann's Construction, the Euler- Savary equation. Inflection Points, the inflection circle; the collineation axis and Bobiller's theorem; Determination of radius of curvature of coupler points by Bobiller's Construction.

    UNIT-4

    Force Analysis of Mechanisms: Equilibrium of two, three and four force bodies; Static force analysis of linkages, principle of super position; Need for dynamics force analysis- D’Alembert’s principle; Determination of inertial forces on linkages; Combined static and dynamics analysis of four bar linkage, Analytical method

    UNIT-5

    Kinematics of Spatial Mechanisms and Robotics: Mobility and description of spatial mechanisms; Position, velocity and acceleration analysis of spatialmechanisms by vector algebra method; Introduction to Robot kinematics, Topological arrangements of robotic arms, Eulerian angles. Denavit - Hartenberg Parameters; Kinematic analysis of robot manipulators using transformation matrices

    INTRODUCTION TO DATA SCIENCE
    UNIT-1 : Introduction

    Data Science Process, the roles in a data science project, stages in data science projects, working with data from files, structured data, working with relational databases and NoSQL databases, managing data, cleaning data, Training and test set split, Structured, semi- structured and unstructured data.

    UNIT-2 : Data Analytics Lifecycle

    Overview, Discovery, Data Preparation, Model planning- Data Exploration and variable selection, Model selection, Common tools for the model planning phases, Model Building, communicate results, Operationalize.

    UNIT-3 : Analytical methods

    Overview of Clustering, K-means, Apriori Algorithm, Evaluation of candidate rules, Applications of association rules, Linear regression, Logistic regression, Decision tree.

    UNIT-4 :Text Analysis

    Text analysis steps, collecting raw text, representing text, creating word cloud, Term frequency- inverse document frequency, categorizing documents by topics, determining sentiments.

    UNIT-5 : Advanced Technology and tools

    Analytics for unstructured data, The Hadoop Ecosystem, NoSQL, SQL Essentials- joins, set operations, Grouping Extensions, Advanced SQL- Window functions, user defined functions and aggregates, ordered aggregates, MADlib.

    BIG DATA ANALYTICS
    UNIT-1

    Introduction to Big Data Analytics: Big Data overview, State of the practice in analytics role of data scientists, Big Data Analytics in industry verticals.

    UNIT-2

    End-to-end Data Analytics Life Cycle: key roles for successful analytic project, main phases of life cycle, developing core deliverables for stakeholders.

    UNIT-3

    Basic Analytic Methods: introduction to “R”, analyzing and exploring data with “R”, Statistics for model building and evaluation.

    UNIT-4

    Advanced Analytics and Statistical Modeling for Big Data: Naïve Bayesian Classifier, K-means Clustering, Association Rules, Decision Trees, Linear and Logistic Regression, Time Series Analysis, Text Analytics

    UNIT-5

    Hadoop: History of Hadoop- The Hadoop Distributed File System – Components of Hadoop Analyzing the Data with Hadoop Developing a Map Reduce Application-How Map Reduce Works-Anatomy of a Map Reduce Job Map Reduce Types and Formats- Map Reduce Features.Frameworks and Big Data Privacy: Applications on Big Data Using Pig and Hive

    PRINCIPLES OF SIGNAL PROCESSING
    UNIT-1 : Introduction

    Introduction to signals and systems, Classification of signals, Periodic and aperiodic Signals, Power and Energy of signals, Operations on signals: Time Shifting, Scaling and reversal, Representation of signals using impulse function, Unit Step f

    UNIT-2 : FOURIER SERIES

    Representation of Fourier series for Continuous time periodic signals, Exponential Fourier series, Trigonometric Fourier series, Symmetry conditions: Even, Odd and Half-wave, Dirichlet’s conditions, properties of Fourier series, Deriving Fourier Transform from Fourier series, Fourier transform of arbitrary signal, standard signals, periodic signals, Properties of Fourier transforms

    UNIT-3 : Discrete Fourier Transforms

    Properties of DFT, Linear Convolution of Sequences using DFT, Computation of DFT, Relation between DTFT, DFT and Z-Transform. Fast Fourier Transforms (FFT), Inverse FFT.

    UNIT-4 : Digital Filters

    Analog filter approximations, Characteristics of IIR Digital Filters, Introduction to Butterworth and Chebyshev filters. Characteristics of FIR Digital Filters, Comparison of IIR & FIR filters.

    UNIT-5

    Down Sampling, Decimation, Up sampling, Interpolation, Sampling Rate Conversion, Conversion of Band Pass Signals, Concept of Resampling, Applications of Multi Rate Signal Processing.

    Battery Management Systems
    UNIT-1 Introduction to Battery Management System

    Introduction, Cells & Batteries, Packs, Nominal voltage and capacity, C rate, Energy and power, Cells connected in series, Cells connected in parallel. Li Ion cells- chemistry, Unequal voltages in series, aging and modelling, Rechargeable cell, Charging and Discharging Process, Overcharge and Undercharge, Modes of Charging

    UNIT-2 :: Battery Management System Requirement

    BMS functionality: CCCV, Regulators, meters, monitoring, balance, protectors. Technology-simple, sophisticated-comparison. Battery pack topology- Centralized, modular, master slave. Li Ion BMSDefinitions, functions, custom versus off the shelf. Li-Ion batteries SOC, DOD and capacity

    UNIT-3 : BMS functions

    BMS functionality: Voltage Sensing, Temperature Sensing, Current Sensing, High-voltage contactor control, Isolation sensing, Thermal control, Protection, Communication Interface, Range estimation, State-of- charge estimation, Cell total energy and cell total power.

    UNIT-4 : Battery State of Charge and State of Health Estimation, Cell Balancing

    state of charge estimation (SOC), voltage-based methods to estimate SOC, Model-based state estimation, Battery Health Estimation, Lithium-ion aging: Negative electrode, Positive electrode, Cell Balancing, Causes of imbalance, Circuits for balancing.

    UNIT-5 : Design of battery BMS

    BMS Design: BMS Application Specific Integrated Circuit (ASIC) selection, Analog BMS design, Digital BMS design, BMS deploying: Installing, testing and troubleshooting.

    Eigenvalues and Eigenvectors and their properties; Diagonalization of a matrix; Cayley-Hamilton Theorem (without proof), finding inverse and powers of a matrix by Cayley-Hamilton Theorem, Real Quadratic form, Matrix representation, Reduction of Quadratic form to canonical form by orthogonal transformation, rank and nature of the quadratic form.

    UNIT-3 : Mean value theorems and Functions of Several Variables

    Model Papers Important Questions
    UNIT-1 : Water and its treatment

    Sources of water, impurities in water, Hardness of water-types, units and numerical problems, Estimation of hardness of water by complexometric method. Defluoridation -Determination of F- ion by ion-selective electrode method. Boiler troubles: Sludges, Scales, boiler corrosion, priming, foaming and Caustic embrittlement. Desalination of water–Reverse osmosis

    Introduction - Classification of batteries- primary, secondary and reserve batteries with examples. Basic requirements for commercial batteries. Construction, working and applications of and Pb-acid battery, Applications of Li-ion battery to electrical vehicles. Fuel Cells -Differences between battery and a fuel cell, Construction and applications of H2 – O2 and Methanol Oxygen fuel cell. Solar cells-Introduction and applications of Solar cells. Corrosion: Introduction, definition, theories of chemical and electrochemical corrosion. Mechanism of electrochemical corrosion, Types of corrosion: Galvanic, water-line and pitting corrosion. Factors affecting rate of corrosion, Corrosion control methods- Cathodic protection–Sacrificial anode and impressed current methods- metallic coating-Galvanizing & tinning.

    UNIT-3 : Lubricants & Phase rule

Rubbers: Natural rubber-Processing and its vulcanization. Elastomers: Characteristics, preparation, properties and applications of Buna-S, Butyl and Thiokol rubber. Biodegradable polymers: Concept and advantages - Poly lactic acid and poly vinyl alcohol and their applications

    UNIT-5 : Fuels

    ADVANCED CALCULUS
    Model Papers Important Questions
    UNIT-1 : Multiple Integrals and Special functions

    Evaluation of Double Integrals: Cartesian and polar coordinates, Change of order of integration (only Cartesian form). Evaluation of Triple Integrals: Change of variables for double (Cartesian to polar) and triple integrals (Cartesian to spherical polar coordinates). Applications: Areas by double integrals and volume by triple integrals. Special functions: Basics of Beta and Gamma Functions.

    UNIT-2 : Laplace Transform

    Laplace transform, Properties of Laplace Transforms (without proof), Laplace transform of periodic functions (without proof). Evaluation of integrals by Laplace transforms. Unit step function – Dirac’s delta function. Finding Inverse Laplace transform by different methods, Convolution theorem (without proof). Solving Ordinary Differential Equations by Laplace Transforms.

    UNIT-3 : Vector Differentiation

    Vector point function and scalar point function, Gradient, Divergence and Curl. Directional Derivatives, Vector identities, Solenoidal, Irrotational vectors and Scalar potential functions.

    UNIT-4 : Vector Integration

    Line integral and Work done by force as a line integral, Surface and Volume Integrals, Green’s, Gauss and Stoke’s Theorems (without proofs) and their applications

    UNIT-5 : Partial Differential Equations

    Introduction to Partial Differential Equations (PDE), Formation of partial differential equations, Solutions of first order linear PDEs using Lagrange’s method, Solutions of first order non-linear standard type PDEs, Solution of PDE using method of separation of variables.

    APPLIED PHYSICS
    Model Papers Important Questions
    UNIT-1 : Fundamentals of Quantum Physics

    Introduction to quantum physics, Dual nature of matter, de-Broglie hypothesis-Concept of matter waves, Davisson and Germer experiment, Wave function and its significance, Schrodinger ime independent wave equation Particle in 1-D potential box, Classical free electron theory (Equation for electrical conductivity), Quantum free electron theory (Qualitative), Fermi-Dirac distribution function and Fermi energy, Kronig-Penny model (Qualitative), Concept of effective mass, Origin of energy bands, Classification of solids.

    UNIT-2 : Semiconductor Physics and Devices

    Semiconductors-Intrinsic semiconductors – Intrinsic carrier concentration, Fermi level, Extrinsic semiconductors (Qualitative)-variation of fermi energy level with respect to temperature and impurity concentration, Hall effect, Formation of PN junction, Working of PN junction diode in forward and reverse bias, V-I Characteristics, Direct and Indirect band gap semiconductors, LED, PIN diode, avalanche photo diode (APD) and solar cells, their structure, working principle and characteristics.

    UNIT-3 : LASERs & Fiber Optics

    Lasers: Introduction, characteristics of LASER, absorption, spontaneous and stimulated emission, Einstein coefficients, Population inversion, Meta stable state, pumping, optical feedback, Ruby laser, He-Ne laser, Semiconductor diode laser, applications of lasers. Fiber Optics Introduction, principle, structure, acceptance angle and numerical aperture, types of fibers: step index and graded index, attenuation in optical fibers, advantages and applications of optical fibers- Concept of fiber laser.

    UNIT-4 : Dielectric and Magnetic Properties

    Dielectric Properties: Types of polarizations: Electronic, Ionic and Orientation polarization (Qualitative), Lorentz fields, Clausius-Mossotti relation, ferroelectric, piezoelectric, and pyroelectric materials – applications – liquid crystal displays (LCD). Magnetic Properties: Origin of magnetic moment, Bohr magneton, Classification of magnetic materials, Weiss domain theory of ferromagnetism, Hysteresis curve, soft and hard magnetic materials, Magnetostriction, Magnetoresistance, Applications: Magnetic field sensors.

    UNIT-5 : Nano Science and Nano Technology

    Nanoscale, Quantum confinement, Surface to Volume ratio, Significance of nanoscience, Properties of Nanomaterials: Physical, Chemical, Mechanical, Optical and Electrical, bottom-up fabrication: chemical vapor deposition (CVD) method – top-down fabrication: ball milling method, Characterization techniques: SEM, TEM, Applications of nanomaterials.

    BASIC ELECTRICAL AND ELECTRONICS ENGINEERING
    UNIT-1 : INTRODUCTION TO ELECTRICAL CIRCUITS

    ohm's law, Kirchhoff's Laws, Network Electrical circuit elements (R, L and C). Types of sources, Source Transformation, reduction techniques-series-parallel-series-parallel-star-to-delta transformation, Mesh, Nodal Analysis. Numerical problems for de excitation (independent sources only). Network Theorems: Thevenin's, Norton's, Superposition theorems- Numeric problems with DC excitation.

    UNIT-2 : SINGLE PHASE A.C CIRCUITS

    Introduction, Sinusoidal alternating quantities, RMS values, Average values, form factor and peak factor, Analysis of single phase ac circuit with series RL, RC & RLC loads, Numerical problems.

    UNIT-3 : ELECTRICAL MACHINES

    DC Machines: Types Construction Details Principle and operation of DC Generator and Motor- EMF equation Applications, Numerical Problems (elementary treatment). AC Machines: Single phase Transformer, Three Phase Induction Motor and Alternator-Construction and Principle of operation, Applications.

    UNIT-4 : P-N JUNCTION DIODE & RECTIFIERS

    P-N Junction Diode: Review of P-N junction diode- V-I Characteristics, Ideal versus Practical, Temperature dependence, Diode as a Switch. Rectifiers: Diode as a Rectifier - Half Wave Rectifier, Full Wave rectifier with center tapped transformer, Bridge Rectifier, Zener diode as regulator.

    UNIT-5 : BIPOLAR JUNCTION TRANSISTOR (BJT)

    P-N Junction Diode: Review of P-N junction diode- V-I Characteristics, Ideal versus Practical, Temperature dependence, Diode as a Switch. Rectifiers: Diode as a Rectifier - Half Wave Rectifier, Full Wave rectifier with center tapped transformer, Bridge Rectifier, Zener diode as regulator.

    Model Papers Important Questions
    UNIT-1

    Basics of Python Programming: Features of Python, History of Python, Variables & Identifiers, Data types, Input/ Output operations, Keywords, Indentation, Operators and Expressions, Type Conversion. Decision Control Statements: Selection/Conditional Branching, Basic Loop Structures/Iterative statements, Nested Loops, Loop manipulation using break, continue and pass statements, else statement used with loops.

    UNIT-2

    Functions and Modules: Use of functions, Function definition, Function call, Variable scope and Lifetime, return statement, argument passing in functions (Required, Keyword, Default, Variable length arguments), Functional Programming: Lambda functions (map, reduce and filter built-in functions), recursive Functions. Strings: Concatenation, appending, multiplying strings, string formatting operator, built-in string methods and functions, slice operation, comparing and iterating strings, the String module.

Dictionaries: Creating, accessing, adding, modifying, deleting, sorting items in a dictionary, Looping over a dictionary, nested dictionaries, built-in functions and methods.

    UNIT-4 : Introduction to Object Oriented Programming

    Classes and Objects: Introduction, Classes and Objects, init( ) method, Class variables, and Object variables, Public and Private Data members, calling a class method from other class methods, built-in functions to check, Get, Set and Delete Class Attributes, built-in class attributes, class methods, static methods. Inheritance: Introduction, inheriting classes: Polymorphism and method overriding, Types of Inheritance, Abstract classes. Operator Overloading: Introduction, Implementation of Operator Overloadin

    UNIT-5

    Error and Exception Handling: Introduction to Errors and Exceptions, Handling Exceptions, multiple except blocks, multiple exceptions in a single block, built-in and user defined exceptions, else clause, finally block. Files: Types of files, Opening and Closing Files, Reading and Writing Files, File Positions Python Libraries and Packages: Introduction to PIP, Installing Packages via PIP, NumPy, SciPy, Pandas, MatplotLib.

    PRESTRESSED CONCRETE
    Model Papers
    UNIT-1

    Introduction: Historic development – general principles of pre stressing pre-tensioning and post tensioning – advantages and limitations of pre stressed concrete – general principles of PSC – classification and types of pre stressing – materials – high strength concrete and high tensile steel their characteristics. Methods and systems of pre stressing: pre tensioning and post tensioning methods and systems of pre stressing like hoyer system, magnel–blaton system, freyssinet system and Gifford – Udall system- lee McCall system

    UNIT-2

    Losses of pre stress: loss of pre-stress in pre-tension and post-tensioned members due to various causes like elastic storage of concrete, shrinkage of concrete, creep of concrete, relaxation of stress in steel, slip in anchorage, frictional losses

    UNIT-3

    FLEXURE: Analysis of sections for flexure – beams pre stressed with straight, concentric, eccentric, bent and parabolic tendons- stress diagrams- elastic design of PSC beams of rectangular and one sections – kern line – cable profile and cable layout. Shear: General considerations – principal tension and compression – improving shear resistance of concrete by horizontal and vertical pre stressing and by using inclined or parabolic cables – analysis of rectangular and I beam for shear

    UNIT-4

    Transfer of pre stress in pre tension members: Transmission of pre stressing force by bond – transmission length – flexural bond stresses –IS code provisions – anchorage zone stresses in post tension members – stress distribution in end block – analysis by GUION, magnet, BIS code provisions.

    UNIT-5

    COMPOSITE BEAMS: Different types – propped and UN propped – stress distribution - differential shrinkage – analysis of composite beams - general design considerations. DEFLECTIONS: Importance of control of deflections – factors influencing deflections – short term deflections of un-cracked beams – prediction of long-time deflections – BIS code requirements

    ADVANCED CALCULUS
    Model Papers Important Questions
    UNIT-1 : Multiple Integrals and Special functions

    Evaluation of Double Integrals: Cartesian and polar coordinates, Change of order of integration (only Cartesian form). Evaluation of Triple Integrals: Change of variables for double (Cartesian to polar) and triple integrals (Cartesian to spherical polar coordinates). Applications: Areas by double integrals and volume by triple integrals. Special functions: Basics of Beta and Gamma Functions.

    UNIT-2 : Laplace Transform

    Laplace transform, Properties of Laplace Transforms (without proof), Laplace transform of periodic functions (without proof). Evaluation of integrals by Laplace transforms. Unit step function – Dirac’s delta function. Finding Inverse Laplace transform by different methods, Convolution theorem (without proof). Solving Ordinary Differential Equations by Laplace Transforms.

    UNIT-3 : Vector Differentiation

    Vector point function and scalar point function, Gradient, Divergence and Curl. Directional Derivatives, Vector identities, Solenoidal, Irrotational vectors and Scalar potential functions.

    UNIT-4 : Vector Integration

    Line integral and Work done by force as a line integral, Surface and Volume Integrals, Green’s, Gauss and Stoke’s Theorems (without proofs) and their applications

    UNIT-5 : Partial Differential Equations

    Introduction to Partial Differential Equations (PDE), Formation of partial differential equations, Solutions of first order linear PDEs using Lagrange’s method, Solutions of first order non-linear standard type PDEs, Solution of PDE using method of separation of variables.

    APPLIED PHYSICS
    Model Papers Important Questions
    UNIT-1 : Fundamentals of Quantum Physics

    Introduction to quantum physics, Dual nature of matter, de-Broglie hypothesis-Concept of matter waves, Davisson and Germer experiment, Wave function and its significance, Schrodinger ime independent wave equation Particle in 1-D potential box, Classical free electron theory (Equation for electrical conductivity), Quantum free electron theory (Qualitative), Fermi-Dirac distribution function and Fermi energy, Kronig-Penny model (Qualitative), Concept of effective mass, Origin of energy bands, Classification of solids.

    UNIT-2 : Semiconductor Physics and Devices

    Semiconductors-Intrinsic semiconductors – Intrinsic carrier concentration, Fermi level, Extrinsic semiconductors (Qualitative)-variation of fermi energy level with respect to temperature and impurity concentration, Hall effect, Formation of PN junction, Working of PN junction diode in forward and reverse bias, V-I Characteristics, Direct and Indirect band gap semiconductors, LED, PIN diode, avalanche photo diode (APD) and solar cells, their structure, working principle and characteristics.

    UNIT-3 : LASERs & Fiber Optics

    Lasers: Introduction, characteristics of LASER, absorption, spontaneous and stimulated emission, Einstein coefficients, Population inversion, Meta stable state, pumping, optical feedback, Ruby laser, He-Ne laser, Semiconductor diode laser, applications of lasers. Fiber Optics Introduction, principle, structure, acceptance angle and numerical aperture, types of fibers: step index and graded index, attenuation in optical fibers, advantages and applications of optical fibers- Concept of fiber laser.

    UNIT-4 : Dielectric and Magnetic Properties

    Dielectric Properties: Types of polarizations: Electronic, Ionic and Orientation polarization (Qualitative), Lorentz fields, Clausius-Mossotti relation, ferroelectric, piezoelectric, and pyroelectric materials – applications – liquid crystal displays (LCD). Magnetic Properties: Origin of magnetic moment, Bohr magneton, Classification of magnetic materials, Weiss domain theory of ferromagnetism, Hysteresis curve, soft and hard magnetic materials, Magnetostriction, Magnetoresistance, Applications: Magnetic field sensors.

    UNIT-5 : Nano Science and Nano Technology

    Nanoscale, Quantum confinement, Surface to Volume ratio, Significance of nanoscience, Properties of Nanomaterials: Physical, Chemical, Mechanical, Optical and Electrical, bottom-up fabrication: chemical vapor deposition (CVD) method – top-down fabrication: ball milling method, Characterization techniques: SEM, TEM, Applications of nanomaterials.

    BASIC ELECTRICAL AND ELECTRONICS ENGINEERING
    UNIT-1 : INTRODUCTION TO ELECTRICAL CIRCUITS

    ohm's law, Kirchhoff's Laws, Network Electrical circuit elements (R, L and C). Types of sources, Source Transformation, reduction techniques-series-parallel-series-parallel-star-to-delta transformation, Mesh, Nodal Analysis. Numerical problems for de excitation (independent sources only). Network Theorems: Thevenin's, Norton's, Superposition theorems- Numeric problems with DC excitation.

    UNIT-2 : SINGLE PHASE A.C CIRCUITS

    Introduction, Sinusoidal alternating quantities, RMS values, Average values, form factor and peak factor, Analysis of single phase ac circuit with series RL, RC & RLC loads, Numerical problems.

    UNIT-3 : ELECTRICAL MACHINES

    DC Machines: Types Construction Details Principle and operation of DC Generator and Motor- EMF equation Applications, Numerical Problems (elementary treatment). AC Machines: Single phase Transformer, Three Phase Induction Motor and Alternator-Construction and Principle of operation, Applications.

    UNIT-4 : P-N JUNCTION DIODE & RECTIFIERS

    P-N Junction Diode: Review of P-N junction diode- V-I Characteristics, Ideal versus Practical, Temperature dependence, Diode as a Switch. Rectifiers: Diode as a Rectifier - Half Wave Rectifier, Full Wave rectifier with center tapped transformer, Bridge Rectifier, Zener diode as regulator.

    UNIT-5 : BIPOLAR JUNCTION TRANSISTOR (BJT)

    4. Full wave rectifier with and without filters.
    5. Common Base (CB) characteristics (Input & output).
    6. Common Emitter (CE) characteristics (Input & output).
    7. Determination of h parameters from CE transistor characteristics.

Generate a bill and display the total amount.

    ENGINEERING GRAPHICS LAB
    List of Experiments

    Week 1:
    ---- Introduction to Engineering Graphics: Principles of engineering graphics and their significance - conventions - use of drawing instruments, lettering - construction of regular polygons
    Week 2:
    ---- Construction of Engineering Scales: Plain, diagonal and vernier scales
    Week 3:
    ---- Construction of Engineering Curves: Conic sections - Ellipse, Parabola, Hyperbola and Cycloids
    Week 4:
    ---- Principles of orthographic projections: First and third angle projections - projections of points in various quadrants
    Week 5:
    ---- Projections of straight lines-I: Parallel to both the planes - parallel to one plane and inclined to the other plane
    Week 6:
    ---- Projections of straight lines-II: Projections of straight lines inclined to both the planes - determination of true lengths, angle of inclinations and traces.
    Week 7:
    ---- Projections of Planes-I: Projections of regular planes - parallel to one plane and perpendicular/inclined to other plane
    Week 8:
    ---- Projections of Planes-II: Projections of planes inclined to both the planes - introduction to auxiliary plane method
    Week 9:
    ---- Projections of Solids-I: Projections of regular solids in simple position - Prism, Cylinder, Pyramid and Cone
    Week 10:
    ---- Projections of Solids-II: Projections of solids axis parallel to one and inclined to other plane
    Week 11:
    ---- Projections of Solids-III: Projections of solids axis inclined to both the planes
    Week 12:
    ---- Isometric Projections
    Week 13:
    ---- Isometric views
    Week 14:
    ---- Conversion of isometric views to orthographic views
